    story: "Key: Deepika Kumari’s journey from the modest village of Ratu in Jharkhand to the pinnacle of world archery is a saga of extraordinary grit. Born into a family with limited means — her father was an auto-rickshaw driver — Deepika’s first 'bows' were made of bamboo, and her 'arrows' were fashioned from tree branches. She used to practice by aiming at mangoes on trees, a humble beginning for an athlete who would eventually become the World No. 1.\n\nHer life changed when she joined the Seraikela-Kharsawan Archery Academy and later the Tata Archery Academy, where she finally got access to professional equipment and coaching. The transition from bamboo to carbon-fiber bows was not just a technical shift, but a psychological one. She quickly dominated the national and international scenes, winning gold at the 2010 Commonwealth Games at just 16. Despite the immense pressure of being India's medal hope in multiple Olympics, she has consistently remained among the world's elite. Her story is a powerful reminder that it doesn't matter where you start; with a laser-like focus and an unbreakable will, you can hit the bullseye on the world stage. Today, she is not just an Olympian; she is an icon for every girl in rural India who dares to reach for the stars.",
