    story: "The Tetseo Sisters are more than just a musical group; they are the cultural guardians of Nagaland’s rich oral traditions. Comprising four sisters—Mutsevelü (Mercy), Azine (Azy), Kuvelü (Kuku), and Alüne (Lulu)—they have dedicated their lives to reviving the traditional 'Li' (folk songs) of the Chakhesang Naga tribe. Growing up in Kohima, they were immersed in the melodies of their ancestors, where stories of bravery, love, and nature were passed down through song.\n\nKey: What sets the Tetseo Sisters apart is their ability to blend these ancient melodies with contemporary folk and pop sounds, accompanied by the traditional 'Tati' (a single-stringed instrument). By performing in their native Chokri dialect on global stages, they have brought the unique sounds of the Northeast to a worldwide audience. They serve as a powerful bridge between the past and the present, ensuring that the younger generation of Nagas feels a sense of pride in their heritage. Their music is an invitation to the world to experience the beauty, depth, and resilience of Naga culture. They remain tireless ambassadors of tribal art, proving that tradition can be both timeless and modern.",
